      "role": "user",
      "content": "okay i get the glove thing, but the \"mystical\" part sounds a bit vague. i read somewhere that einstein called it \"spooky action at a distance\" because it seemed so weird. is there a more scientific way to describe that \"spookiness\" or why it's so different from just things being hidden from us beforehand?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Einstein did indeed call it \"spooky action at a distance\" because it seemed so strange and counterintuitive. The \"spookiness\" comes from the fact that entangled particles appear to affect each other instantaneously, even when separated by vast distances. This defies our usual understanding of how the world works, where objects are only influenced by their immediate surroundings and not by distant events.\n\nIn more scientific terms, the \"spookiness\" is a result of the non-locality of quantum mechanics. Non-locality means that the properties of entangled particles are not determined until they are measured, and the measurement of one particle instantly determines the state of the other, regardless of the distance between them. This is different from classical physics, where objects are only influenced by their immediate surroundings and not by distant events.\n\nThe \"spookiness\" is also related to the concept of superposition, where particles can exist in multiple states at once until they are measured. When two particles are entangled, they are in a superposition of states, and the measurement of one particle collapses the superposition, determining the state of the other particle instantly. This instantaneous collapse of the superposition is what Einstein found so \"spooky.\"\n\nIn summary",
      "source": "target",
